{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01Ub269TrxyqC5MSe52eRBkW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking me to write a test plan for a content moderation service issue. I need to analyze each of the 6 behaviors and determine:\n\n1. The minimum test level needed to catch a real failure\n2. A description of what the behavior does\n3. A justification for why that level is needed\n4. A test description\n5. Whether the test is consistent with the plan\n6. Probability distribution across the 5 levels\n\nLet me think through each behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.**\n\n- This depends on the AI vision model producing a classification\n- We need the model to actually identify explicit content\n- Could we mock the vision model? We could mock it to say \"explicit\", but that doesn't test if the real model would actually catch explicit content\n- The key failure is: what if the real model doesn't catch explicit content, or what if the pipeline logic doesn't properly flag it?\n- Minimum level: **Agentic** - because correctness depends on what a real vision model produces. A mock could always return \"explicit\", but the real model might miss actual explicit content.\n- A pure Unit test with a mocked model would always pass\n- A pure Integration test that mocks the model would also pass but not catch real model failures\n- We need the real vision model to verify the behavior\n\n**Behavior 2: A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).**\n\n- This also depends on the AI text model's ability to detect obfuscated hate speech\n- Could we mock the text model? We could, but we wouldn't verify the real model catches obfuscated hate speech\n- Minimum level: **Agentic** - because correctness depends on what a real text classification model produces\n- The real challenge is: can the real model handle obfuscation? Mocking it won't tell us\n\n\n- For Behavior 3, the logic is straightforward: if both models return \"safe\", publish the post. This is deterministic and can be tested with mocked models. The real risk is a logic error in the pipeline or the post not actually being published to the right destination. We need Integration level to verify the complete flow and confirm the post reaches its intended state, but we don't need real models since we're testing the orchestration logic, not model accuracy.\n\n- For Behavior 4, we're looking at performance constraints—the entire moderation pipeline needs to complete within 5 seconds.\n- Real model latency is essential here; mocking them to run instantly would mask actual bottlenecks.\n- Whether the models execute as local subprocesses, HTTP calls to external services, or library imports, we're dealing with real infrastructure dependencies that can't be abstracted away.\n- This pushes the requirement to **System** level testing—we need actual execution with genuine network and processing delays to validate the 5-second constraint.\n\nFor the vision model unavailability scenario, mocking an exception would only verify the error path executes, not whether the retry queue mechanism truly functions. Testing \"queued for retry\" demands checking that items actually enter the queue, get processed by the retry system later, and don't slip through to auto-approval in the interim. This requires either a real message broker or a functional queue implementation, not just an exception-throwing mock.\n\nThe minimum viable level is Integration—wiring the error handler to the queue and confirming items are queued rather than auto-approved. Whether it's System or Integration depends on the queue implementation: a real external broker pushes it to System level, while an in-memory or local database queue keeps it at Integration. For most production systems, a real queue would make this System level, but Integration testing with a mock or local queue suffices to catch the core failure mode.\n\nFor behavior 5 specifically, the critical issue is preventing auto-approval when the model fails. A Unit test with mocked dependencies would catch if the logic incorrectly approves instead of queuing. An Integration test would verify the queue is actually invoked and receives the item. A System test would expose issues with the queue implementation itself—threading, persistence, message loss. Since the queue is likely a separate module, Integration is the minimum needed to confirm the logic correctly delegates to it. → System if it's a real message broker, or Integration if it's an in-memory queue or database table.\n\nFor this exercise, I'm assuming a real message broker in production, so System level would be appropriate. Though rereading behavior 5—\"image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved\"—the core requirement is preventing auto-approval and ensuring queueing happens. If the queue is just a database table, Integration testing would suffice. I'll go with Integration as the minimum, noting that a production system with a distributed message broker would warrant System-level testing. The real failures I'm trying to catch are logic errors (approving when the model is unavailable instead of queuing) and concurrency issues. race condition in queueing → Integration/System\n3. Queue failure: queue doesn't actually persist the message → System\n4. Model failure: model is never actually called, so unavailability isn't detected → Integration/System\n\nFor robustness, I'd say Integration minimum (to verify the queue mechanism is called), but System would be needed to catch queue persistence failures.\n\nLet me go with Integration level for behavior 5, with the understanding that System would be more robust.\n\nActually, I should reconsider the levels more carefully. Looking at the definitions again:\n\n- **Unit** — one local function or object boundary, no I/O\n- **Integration** — several modules wired together, local DB or filesystem\n- **System** — subprocess, OS behavior, real HTTP, or real external API call\n- **Agentic** — result depends on real LLM non-determinism or a real AI/ML model call\n- **Workflow** — multiple agentic steps in sequence, or a full agent pipeline\n\nWith this in mind, behavior 1 (image flagged as explicit) requires **Agentic** level since it depends on the real vision model's classification accuracy—mocking the model wouldn't catch cases where the actual model fails to detect explicit content. Behavior 2 (text with obfuscation flagged as hate speech) similarly needs **Agentic** level because detecting obfuscated hate speech relies on the real text model's capabilities.\n\nBehavior 3 (safe post published) can be tested at **Integration** level by mocking both models to return \"safe\" and verifying the post flows through the decision logic and publisher. Behavior 4 (pipeline completes in 5 seconds) requires **System** level since real model latencies and network delays would be hidden by mocks. Behavior 5 (unavailable model triggers retry queue) sits at **Integration** level—I can mock the model to fail and verify the queue receives the item and no auto-approval occurs, though **System** would be stronger if the queue itself is external.\n\nFor Behavior 6, I need **Agentic** level testing because consistency across multiple submissions depends on the real model's actual behavior. Mocking wouldn't reveal whether the model gives deterministic results for the same input.\n\nNow assigning probability distributions: Behavior 1 has 0.0 for Unit (can't test real model there), 0.05 for Integration (mocks hide real failures), 0.1 for System (HTTP calls might be needed but doesn't test non-determinism), and 0.8 for Agentic since that's where the real model's robustness to obfuscation becomes critical.\n\nBehavior 2 follows a similar pattern—0.0 Unit, 0.05 Integration, 0.1 System, 0.8 Agentic (testing the actual text model's ability to catch obfuscated hate speech), and 0.05 Workflow.\n\nFor Behavior 3, publication logic requires wiring together decision components and the publisher with mocked models, making Integration the dominant level at 0.85. Unit testing can't cover the full publication flow, System adds little value since the main concern is logic correctness rather than real HTTP calls, and Agentic isn't needed here.\n\nBehavior 4 shifts focus to latency—Unit is 0.0 since real timing can't be measured in isolation, Integration with mocks would mask actual latencies, System dominates at 0.8 because real model latencies and network conditions matter, and Agentic is 0.1 since real models are involved but the emphasis is performance rather than accuracy.\n\nBehavior 5 tests queue behavior with mostly Integration-level testing at 0.75, verifying the queue receives items without auto-approval. Unit could work with in-memory mocks at 0.05, System might be needed if the queue is external at 0.15, and real models aren't required.\n\nBehavior 6 requires a real model, so Unit testing alone won't suffice.\n\nFor the remaining behaviors, Integration testing with mocked models can't validate consistency across runs, System testing with actual HTTP calls to real models becomes necessary at 0.1, and Agentic testing dominates at 0.8 since model consistency depends on real inference behavior. These could integrate into the broader pipeline but the core validation happens at the Agentic level.\n\nReconsidering the probability framework—these should reflect confidence that each level represents the minimum sufficient testing. For behavior 1 with explicit content detection, Unit-level testing can't catch failures in the model's detection capability itself, only logic errors like skipping the model call entirely, so that's around 0.01. Integration with mocks might always return \"explicit\" but wouldn't validate the real model's detection, roughly 0.05. System testing partially addresses this by running actual detection, though it still depends on whether the real model performs correctly.\n\nThe core issue is distinguishing between what each level can actually catch: Unit and Integration test the logic flow with controlled inputs, but neither validates whether the real model detects explicit content. System and Agentic levels test against actual model behavior, with Agentic testing capturing non-determinism across multiple runs. The failure mode—explicit content not being flagged—requires testing against the real model's actual detection capability, which only happens at System level and above. test the full pipeline. Unit testing won't expose model-level failures. Integration testing with mocked models could catch logic errors but might miss what the actual model does. System and Workflow levels are less likely to be where the core issue surfaces. The real question is whether the failure stems from the model's ability to detect explicit content—which only a real model can reveal—or from how the logic handles the model's output. Given the service's dependence on the vision model's correctness, the minimum level needed is Agentic testing with the actual model.\n\nFor behavior 1, the critical boundary is the model's real-world performance at identifying explicit content, so Agentic is necessary. For behavior 3, the failure boundary is the deterministic logic that decides whether to publish, which Integration testing with mocked models can validate.\n\nBehavior 4 depends on actual latencies across the pipeline—models, network calls, system performance—requiring System-level testing to measure the 5-second constraint. Behavior 5's failure boundary involves error handling and queue mechanics; assuming a local in-memory queue, Integration testing suffices. Behavior 6 requires testing the real model's consistency on identical inputs, making Agentic the minimum level.\n\nFor the confidence distributions, I'm assigning probabilities across levels based on where the actual failure might occur. Behavior 1 most likely fails at the Agentic level (0.75 confidence), but could potentially surface at Integration (0.1) if it's a logic issue, or System (0.1) if it's an HTTP problem with the model service, with minimal probability elsewhere.\n\nI also need to verify plan consistency—whether my test descriptions actually demand the level I've chosen. If I claim Agentic-level testing but my description uses mocked components, that's inconsistent. The test should genuinely require real images and real model calls if I'm asserting Agentic is the minimum.\n\nFor Behavior 1, the test genuinely needs a real vision model to detect explicit content in actual images. Mocking would mask failures where the real model fails to identify problematic content. The test description reflects this: submitting an actual image with explicit material and confirming the model flags it correctly and prevents publication. This is consistent with Agentic level, so plan_consistent is true.\n\nFor Behavior 2, obfuscated hate speech requires the real text model to demonstrate robustness against character substitutions and unicode tricks. A mocked model can't validate this capability—it would just return the expected result regardless of input. The test involves submitting posts with obfuscated slurs and verifying the model catches them and holds the content for review. This aligns with Agentic level testing, making plan_consistent true.\n\nFor Behavior 3, the focus shifts to decision logic rather than model capability. Since the requirement is simply that safe classifications from both models trigger publication, mocked models work fine here. Integration level is sufficient because the test needs to verify the decision logic actually calls the publisher when both checks pass, not just that the logic itself is sound.\n\nFor Behavior 4, real latencies matter. Mocking the models would mask whether the actual pipeline meets the 5-second requirement, so System level testing with genuine model calls is necessary to catch real performance bottlenecks.\n\nThe test submits a post with image and text through the actual moderation pipeline, measuring end-to-end latency from submission through the vision model, text model, decision logic, and final database or queue write. This confirms the entire flow completes within the 5-second budget.\n\nFor the unavailable model scenario, I need to verify that when the vision model fails, the system queues the image for retry rather than auto-approving it. This is a logic verification—mocking the model's failure is sufficient to check the error handling path. The test mocks a connection error or timeout from the vision model, submits an image post, and confirms the image gets added to the retry queue with a \"pending\" status rather than being published immediately.\n\nFor the borderline consistency check, a real vision model is essential since mocking would always return identical results and wouldn't catch actual inconsistencies. The test needs to submit the same borderline image multiple times and verify the model produces consistent classifications each time, catching cases where the real model might fluctuate on edge-case decisions.\n\nThe test would use a borderline image (like mildly suggestive content), submit it 5+ times within a short timeframe, and confirm the classification remains the same across all submissions. Different results would indicate a failure in consistency.\n\nReconsidering the level probabilities: the key question is whether running this test 100 times with the real model would produce varying outcomes. For an explicit image, the model should consistently flag it as explicit unless it's highly non-deterministic. But I need to think through whether the model's behavior is truly deterministic or if there's inherent variability in how it classifies borderline cases.\n\nFor the consistency test, I'm checking whether the model produces the same output across multiple runs—so by definition, outcomes either vary or they don't. This is fundamentally about the model's determinism, making it an agentic-level concern since I'm verifying the real model's actual behavior rather than testing a deterministic system.\n\nReconsidering the level_probabilities: I'm expressing confidence about which level represents the minimum needed, not certainty. For behavior 1, I'm fairly confident Agentic is the floor (0.8), with smaller chances it could be Integration (0.1), System (0.05), or something else (0.05). The distributions capture my uncertainty about where the actual minimum sits. For behavior 4, I need to verify the real image check component and text check component both execute within the time constraint, which requires testing the actual pipeline rather than mocking it out. System as the minimum level for behavior 4, with a note that Agentic testing would be needed to fully validate model latencies.\n\nThe key question is what failure modes we're actually trying to catch. Integration-level tests won't surface real model latency issues since they use mocks, but System-level tests with actual model calls would catch slowdowns in vision processing or database operations. Pipeline logic itself is typically fast, so the real bottlenecks are external dependencies. That makes System the practical minimum, though Agentic-level validation would be more comprehensive for understanding actual model performance on production data.\n\nI should clarify the distinction between System and Agentic levels too. System covers real HTTP calls and external APIs, while Agentic specifically requires non-deterministic LLM behavior to matter for correctness. For behavior 4, latency testing doesn't depend on what the model outputs—just how long it takes—so System is the right fit. Behavior 1 is different because it cares about whether the model correctly identifies explicit content, making Agentic necessary. For behavior 5, I need to verify whether Integration level actually works or if we need System-level mocking of the unavailable model. the model unavailable (mock it to fail)\n2. Submit an image\n3. Verify it's queued, not auto-approved\n\nThis doesn't require the real model (mocking its failure is fine). It doesn't require real infrastructure unless the queue is external.\n\nSo minimum level is Integration (mocked model, local queue).\n\nBut if the queue is a real distributed message broker (e.g., RabbitMQ), then System level might be needed to verify the message is actually persisted and not lost.\n\nI'll assume a local queue (in-memory or database), so Integration is the minimum.\n\nAlright, I think I'm ready to write the final output.\n\nLet me organize the behaviors:\n\n1. Image with explicit content is flagged → Agentic\n2. Text with obfuscation is flagged → Agentic\n3. Safe post is published → Integration\n4. Pipeline completes in 5 seconds → System\n5. Unavailable model triggers retry queue → Integration\n6. Borderline image decision is consistent → Agentic\n\nFor the performance behavior, I need to verify it actually depends on real infrastructure—the vision and text model subprocesses, real database writes, and OS-level scheduling all affect whether the pipeline meets the 5-second threshold. That confirms System level is appropriate. Now I should validate the probability distributions sum to 1.0 across all behaviors before finalizing the output. database/queue writes. This requires real model calls, so it's appropriate for the System level. ✓\n\nFor behavior 5, the test involves mocking the vision model to simulate unavailability and checking that posts enter a retry queue with proper status tracking—this fits Integration level. ✓\n\nFor behavior 6, I'm submitting a borderline image multiple times to verify consistency in the vision model's classifications. If the model returns different results across submissions, that indicates an issue with reliability or determinism that the test should catch.\n\nThis requires Agentic level since it involves real borderline content and multiple submissions to validate consistent behavior. ✓\n\nAll tests align with their assigned levels. Now I'll format the output as JSON.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13513,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13513},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"03db7d5d-3599-4760-ae91-5f50a225e1a5","uuid":"8139827b-71af-41d5-9bb7-7bed26d8c7a5"}
